6 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
7 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
8 Article – Criminal Law
9 10–110.
10 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
11 (4) “Litter” means all rubbish, waste matter, refuse, garbage, trash, debris,
12 dead animals, or other discarded materials of every kind and description.
13 (c) A person may not:
14 (1) dispose of litter on a highway or perform an act that violates the State
15 Vehicle Laws regarding disposal of litter, glass, and other prohibited substances on
16 highways; or
17 (2) dispose or cause or allow the disposal of litter on public or private
18 property unless:
19 (i) the property is designated by the State, a unit of the State, or a
20 political subdivision of the State for the disposal of litter and the person is authorized by
21 the proper public authority to use the property; or
22 (ii) the litter is placed into a litter receptacle or container installed
23 on the property.
24 (f) (1) A person who violates this section is subject to the penalties provided
25 in this subsection.
26 (2) (i) A person who disposes of litter in violation of this section in an
27 amount not exceeding 100 pounds or 27 cubic feet and not for commercial gain is guilty of
28 a misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to imprisonment not exceeding 30 days or a
29 fine not exceeding $1,500 or both.
30 (ii) A person who disposes of litter in violation of this section in an
31 amount exceeding 100 pounds or 27 cubic feet, but not exceeding 500 pounds or 216 cubic
32 feet, and not for commercial gain is guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to
33 imprisonment not exceeding 1 year or a fine not exceeding $12,500 or both.

SENATE BILL 525 3
1 (iii) A person who disposes of litter in violation of this section in an
2 amount exceeding 500 pounds or 216 cubic feet or in any amount for commercial gain is
3 guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to imprisonment not exceeding 5 years
4 or a fine not exceeding $30,000 or both.
5 (i) (1) Fines collected for violations of this section shall be disbursed:
6 (i) to the county or municipal corporation where the violation
7 occurred; or
8 (ii) if the bi–county unit is the enforcement unit and the violations
9 occurred on property over which the bi–county unit exercises jurisdiction, to the bi–county
10 unit.
11 (2) Fines collected shall be used to pay for:
12 (I) litter receptacles and posting signs as required by subsection (h)
13 of this section and for other purposes relating to the removal or control of litter; AND
14 (II) REWARDS TO MEMBERS OF THE PUBLIC WHO SUBMIT VIDEO
15 EVIDENCE THROUGH A PROGRAM ESTABLISHED UNDER SUBSECTION (K) OF THIS
16 SECTION.
17 (K) (1) EACH COUNTY SHALL THE GOVERNING BODY FOR PRINCE
18 GEORGE’S COUNTY MAY ESTABLISH A PILOT PROGRAM ALLOWING A MEMBER OF
19 THE PUBLIC TO:
20 (1) (I) SUBMIT VIDEO EVIDENCE OF AN ALLEGED VIOLATION OF
21 THIS SECTION TO AN ENFORCEMENT UNIT WITH JURISDICTION; AND
22 (2) RECEIVE “HALF THE TOTAL AMOUNT” OF ANY FINES COLLECTED
23 (II) RECEIVE HALF THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF ANY FINES
24 COLLECTED IN RELATION TO THE VIOLATION IF THE VIDEO EVIDENCE LEADS TO A
25 CONVICTION UNDER THIS SECTION.
26 (2) IF A PERSON FINED UNDER THIS SUBSECTION DOES NOT PAY THE
27 FINE, THE COURT MAY REFER THE AMOUNT OF THE UNPAID OUTSTANDING FINE TO
28 THE CENTRAL COLLECTION UNIT OF THE DEPARTMENT OF BUDGET AND
29 MANAGEMENT.
30 [(k)] (L) This section may be cited as the “Illegal Dumping and Litter Control
31 Law”.

